      "side": 1,
      "message": "nit: if zip has many files, this might eat up memory. (It looks like there is a pool of decompressors, where f.Open() grabs from this pool and rc.Close() releases back to the pool.)\n\nEric has started doing a lispy thing like:\nfunc withZipFileReader(f *zip.File, fn func(rc io.ReadCloser) error) error {\n  rc, err :\u003d f.Open()\n  if err !\u003d nil {\n    return err\n  }\n  if err :\u003d fn(rc); err !\u003d nil {\n    return err\n  }\n  return rc.Close();\n}\n\nOr maybe this would be better:\n\nfunc forZipFile(r *zip.ReadCloser, fn func(f *zip.File, rc io.ReadCloser) error) error {\n  for _, f :\u003d range r.File {\n    rc, err :\u003d f.Open()\n    if err !\u003d nil {\n      return err\n    }\n    if err :\u003d fn(f, rc); err !\u003d nil {\n      return err\n    }\n    if err :\u003d rc.Close(); err !\u003d nil {\n      return err\n    }\n  }\n  return nil\n}",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 24,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 24,
        "endChar": 17
      },
